nt &quot;position&quot;. And otherwise: that depends. Some genomes are more stable than others. Some genes are, too."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7bbc24925ff1139a376980af9bd8279d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17429,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17429/ahmed-abdullah","reputation":150,"display_name":"Ahmed Abdullah","accept_rate":38},"score":1,"post_id":40902,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448269393,"comment_id":69188,"body":"There are bacteria with linear chromosome. <a href=\"https://microbewiki.kenyon.edu/index.php/Chromosomes_in_Bacteria:_Are_they_all_single_and_circular%3F#Summary_of_Currently_Known_Bacterial_Chromosome_Organizations\" rel=\"nofollow\">microbewiki.kenyon.edu/index.php/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":1,"post_id":40902,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448287739,"comment_id":69194,"body":"Yes, but are those the species you are working with?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef10e56567f5d6e20bc3f7f4ab4e3254?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":87,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/87/gaurav","reputation":683,"display_name":"Gaurav"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1448923447,"creation_date":1448923447,"body":"<p>The locations of a gene on a bacterial chromosome is determined arbitrarily, so you would not expect coding sequences to necessarily have the same numerical values. Remember that the bacteria's transcription machinery will use <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Promoter_%28genetics%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">promoters<\/a> in the genetic sequence to determine where to start transcription, so the actual start location doesn't really matter -- it's pretty easy for random mutations to add or delete a few base pairs between several genes!<\/p>\n\n<p>Instead, you would search for the genetic sequence of the gene you were interested in on the genome of a closely related species. Since many genomes are annotated by identifying genes from closely related species, it is <em>possible<\/em> that two closely related genomes start at exactly the same place, but you should definitely not assume that this will always be the case.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41131,"question_id":40902,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2442ea911c89187262d6575d739a1ca7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5148/swbarnes2","reputation":1824,"display_name":"swbarnes2"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461949751,"creation_date":1461949751,"body":"<p>If all your samples are, say, E,coli K12 MG1655, there will be very little difference between the published sequence and what you have.  If you have another strain of E.coli, you can't count on there being no indels at all between the two strains.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45727,"question_id":40902,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40902/how-much-genomic-variation-one-usually-find-within-a-given-bacterial-species","last_activity_date":1461949751,"creation_date":1448259431,"answer_count":2,"title":"How much genomic variation one usually find within a given bacterial species?","body":"<p>If I find the exact starting position (say 1152471) of the coding sequence of a given gene in the genome of a bacterium, is the genome of the bacterium in general stable enough so that I can expect to find the same position in a different member of the same species? <\/p>\n","question_id":40902,"tags":["bioinformatics","bacteriology","genomics","genomes"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":63,"up_vot