y","cell-biology","metabolism","photosynthesis"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":44591,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":68,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1458793828},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/26c33f6120956a33e8856f5904392e68?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":9143,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9143/rader","reputation":16,"display_name":"Rader"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fc54887ecbaba35e17251129e5b78c9a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1486,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1486/bli","reputation":812,"display_name":"bli"},"score":0,"post_id":21130,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410270941,"comment_id":33183,"body":"Could it be that the bird was holding something into its beak, which made it look curved?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/41CJK.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5762,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5762/the-last-word","reputation":4553,"display_name":"The Last Word","accept_rate":100},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1410328721,"creation_date":1410328721,"body":"<p>It could be a crow, a blackbird or a raven for all we know because deformed bills on birds has been a matter of debate (<a href=\"http://www.rrbo.org/conservation-science/research/bird-banding/bill-deformities/\" rel=\"nofollow\">reference<\/a>) and there is a group on flickr (<a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/groups/badbills/\" rel=\"nofollow\">reference<\/a>) where you can post such pictures. I have actually noticed few pictures of birds with beaks that resemble the one in your photo. <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/D4tNm.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\">\nA crow with a deformed bill (<a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/25348030@N07/9470671637/in/pool-badbills\" rel=\"nofollow\">refe