/p>\n  \n  <p>NaCl 10 g<\/p>\n  \n  <p>1 M NaOH 1.0 ml<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Autoclave (151b/in^2, 30 min). For LB agar plates solidify with 1.5% (w/v)\n  agar; for LB overlay use 0.7% agar.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The first three components and their corresponding amounts are the same as what I normally work with, but I usually add distilled water for plating E. coli instead of NaOH. According to Wikipedia's entry on lysogeny broth, NaOH can be added to adjust LB's pH. But the protocol here mentions nothing of that sort. In other protocols of the book, at least it would say \"adjust to pH -- with 10 M NaOH\" or 1 M NaOH, etc. So if it is not to adjust the pH for the growth of <em>Bacillus subtilis<\/em>, what other purpose does NaOH do for the bacteria?<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, I usually autoclave my LB or LB-agar for 2 hours instead of 30 minutes. Would autoclaving at 2 hours instead of 30 minutes affect NaOH?<\/p>\n","question_id":37429,"tags":["bacteriology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":70,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f33cf81a416869df7edd12a9f219ca45?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4235,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4235/gerard","reputation":111,"display_name":"Gerard"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1376502519,"creation_date":1376502519,"body":"<p>Swallowing food requires muscle strength to force the food down the oesophagus, which is a soft tube that collapses when empty, simply because the body is very crowded (space-efficient) and empty spaces collapse unless forced open. Only when you swallow, the oesophageal muscles force space to be made for food coming through.<\/p>\n\n<p>In contrast, the trachea and bronchi are covered in almost-circular or C-shaped cartilage which holds them open and stable for air to flow through. You can see it here: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bronchi\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bronchi<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Concluding, air does not enter the oesophagus because it is always closed. Additionally, when the chest expands for breathing, the lungs expand and create suction down the trachea and not into the stomach (simply because this is where they connect).<\/p>\n\n<p>The exception of course is if air is trapped in the swallowing motion with (or without) food. In this case it <em>will<\/em> enter the oesophagus and cause you to burp.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9776,"question_id":9775,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9775/why-does-air-from-the-nasal-cavity-not-go-into-the-oesophagus","last_activity_date":1461869713,"creation_date":1376497168,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does air from the nasal cavity not go into the oesophagus?","body":"<p>When we ingest food, the epiglottis covers the trachea and the uvula covers the nasal passage. But what happens when we breathe? Why does the air go into our trachea and not the oesophagus? <\/p>\n","question_id":9775,"tags":["human-biology","breathing"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1461870461,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1068,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fa5e946e05dd13224f520d76fe716a32?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17291,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17291/john-walthour","reputation":148,"display_name":"John Walthour"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45693/can-plant-roots-absorb-dissolved-oxygen-from-water-or-do-they-require-actual-bu","last_activity_date":1461866798,"creation_date":1461866410,"answer_count":0,"title":"Can plant roots ab