for most sites humans and chimps have the same allele, there are many cases where the ancestral allele is even completely absent from humans, and where all humans have a different allele from chimpanzees, which we call a substitution.<\/p>\n\n<p>A substitution in a critical part of a protein can indeed indicate some biological significance, a classical example is the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FOXP2\" rel=\"nofollow\">FOXP2<\/a> gene, that is related to speech development. In most cases however, substitutions are merely due to genetic drift occurring over millions of years.<\/p>\n","answer_id":36563,"question_id":36505,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36505/ancestral-allele-and-hapmap","last_activity_date":1461866556,"creation_date":1438313417,"answer_count":1,"title":"Ancestral Allele and Hapmap","body":"<p>I notice on dbSNP rs6352 has an ancestral allele of G - <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/SNP/snp_ref.cgi?rs=rs6352\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/SNP/snp_ref.cgi?rs=rs6352<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The hapmap in humans for this allele is very rare, the homozygous version practically not existing at all <a href=\"http://hapmap.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-perl/snp_details_phase3?name=rs6352&amp;source=hapmap3r3_B36&amp;tmpl=snp_details_phase3\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://hapmap.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-perl/snp_details_phase3?name=rs6352&amp;source=hapmap3r3_B36&amp;tmpl=snp_details_phase3<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>My understanding has been that the ancestral allele refers to the common gene that an ancestor in all humans once shared. Now, I thought the ancestral allele was usually the most frequent in a population, but I can see this was most likely a wrong assumption.<\/p>\n\n<p>Was it a wrong assumption, or was this example above just a rare exception? Is deviation from ancestral alleles nearly worthless as a metric to investigate possible mutated alleles that may be leading to disease? I realize the proper answer may be too long, but just a brief summary would be appreciated. <\/p>\n\n<p>Many thanks.<\/p>\n","question_id":36505,"tags":["genetics"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":68,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/12645082ebc4ed9f77743ad5c69e56b9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23557,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23557/user23557","reputation":1,"display_name":"user23557"},"closed_date":1461875183,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45691/i-have-situs-inversus-totalus-and-was-wondering-if-this-would-effect-my-chances","last_activity_date":1461862925,"creation_date":1461862925,"answer_count":0,"title":"I have situs inversus totalus and was wondering if this would effect my chances of getting pregnant","body":"<p>I have asked doctors and was never given a reAL answer<\/p>\n","question_id":45691,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":false,"view_count":17,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/BtNnN.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14893,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14893/melchior-philips","reputation":6,"display_name":"Melchior Philips"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":1,"post_id":45687,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461854620,"comment_id":80118,"body":"Think: The response ramped up due to antigenic challenge. Antigenic challenge has dropped off. Consider that effector cells require signals, and signals are produced in response to antigenic challenge."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45687/how-does-the-body-know-to-stop-effector-cell-proliferation","l