y and preys seeing from above would see a black background and those seeing from below would see a lighter background."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a57e9d301c04907195dd93a855b3bd37?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15199,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15199/medley56","reputation":45,"display_name":"medley56"},"score":0,"post_id":31025,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428040330,"comment_id":51746,"body":"Clarification: I am familiar with concepts such as genetic drift and non-adaptive mutations. Given that the Orca is an apex predator, I could certainly believe that coloration doesn&#39;t confer much interspecies competitive advantage. If I were pressed to guess, I would actually guess sexual selection. I was just hoping someone actually had a theory (i.e. with some evidence) on <i>which<\/i> evolutionary process governs it."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a57e9d301c04907195dd93a855b3bd37?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15199,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15199/medley56","reputation":45,"display_name":"medley56"},"score":0,"post_id":31025,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1428040501,"comment_id":51747,"body":"Also, @Remi.b, I totally agree, countershading makes perfect sense. I guess was referring more to the black and white eye spots and the other well-known splotchy patterns."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c0cf46c3426ba3b0eebe6163d1aa130?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6003,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6003/dan-horvat","reputation":304,"display_name":"Dan Horvat"},"score":0,"post_id":31025,"edited":false,"