 energy source. DNA synthesis requires ATP. RNA synthesis requires ATP. Protein synthesis requires ATP."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/eX5bB.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23529,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23529/henry-stone","reputation":11,"display_name":"Henry Stone"},"score":0,"post_id":45657,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461776003,"comment_id":80053,"body":"So the ATP proces did exist in early cyanobacteria? Was it mitochindrial?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4ce918b1ee86a35bf1d21fcfb589f99c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1640,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1640/dermot-harnett","reputation":380,"display_name":"Dermot Harnett"},"score":0,"post_id":45657,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/eX5bB.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23529,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23529/henry-stone","reputation":11,"display_name":"Henry Stone"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461779489,"comment_id":80054,"body":"ATP is found in  all known organisms, so there&#39;s every reason to think it would have been. Bacteria don&#39;t have mitochondria, so no, it wouldn&#39;t have been mitochondrial."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/eX5bB.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23529,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23529/henry-stone","reputation":11,"display_name":"Henry Stone"},"score":0,"post_id":45657,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461784921,"comment_id":80065,"body":"Sorry, I meant that there was a photosynthetiv ATP, i.e. a more powerful one than in non-photosynthetic anaerobic organisms."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6548cab22512d06e9ee2aefa2793d427?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22364,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22364/jory","reputation":441,"display_name":"Jory"},"score":1,"post_id":45657,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461823665,"comment_id":80080,"body":"Mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation and cyanobacterial photosynthesis are really two special cases of electron transport chains, which come in endless forms. They all follow the same principle, namely the transfer of high energy electrons redox acceptors, favourable reactions which release energy that can be harnessed. The donor of high energy electrons can be anything (NADH in oxphos or P700 for photosynthesis) and the electron acceptor just has to have a more negative redox potential than the donor. As long as the transfer of the electron from the donor to the acceptor releases.."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6548cab22512d06e9ee2aefa2793d427?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22364,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22364/jory","reputation":441,"display_name":"Jory"},"score":0,"post_id":45657,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461823993,"comment_id":80081,"body":"energy, it can be harvested. In the case of photosynthesis, donor electron is only so high in energy because the reaction centers transfer energy to it from the sun&#39;s radiation. By contrast the donor electron in oxphos is high in energy initially, with the energy input coming from the initial synthesis of food molecules. There is really an amazing variety of these electron transport chains, which often use similar enzymes and electron transfer machinery, but have extremely varied high energy donors and oxidizing acceptors. It could be both are inorganic compounds like sulfur and nitrates."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6548cab22512d06e9ee2aefa2793d427?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22364,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22364/jory","reputation":441,"display_name":"Jory"},"score":0,"post_id":45657,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461824492,"comment_id":80082,"body":"Often the energy is used to pump ions across a membrane to synthesize ATP using the stored energy of the electrochemical gradient, as occurs in the mitochondrial membrane. In most bacteria this occurs in the cell membrane, which nicely illustrates the endosymbiotic (bacterial) origin of mitochondria. Some phototrophs transfer energy to electrons using the sun&#39;s radiation, but then simply use that energized electron to form a chemical bond (instead of pumping ions), which can be broken to release energy and the low energy electron. So, there even are ways to store food aside from sugar and ATP."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461772156,"creation_date":1461772156,"body":"<p>Why do you think that the only benefit from photosynthesis is polysaccharide synthesis? Photosynthesis allows an organism to convert photons into chemical energy. That chemical energy can be stored as polysaccharides and used as a building material, but it can also just be converted into some other compound, or just used to run the organisms metabolism, which is the real significance of photosynthesis and the reason it supports most of the world's ecosystems. <\/p>\n","answer_id":45657,"question_id":45654,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461785671,"creation_date":1461783114,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>But cyanobacteria do not seem to use polysaccharides in the same way as plant cells do (building materials, for example)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<ol>\n<li>The Calvin-Benson cycle produces glucose which is the starting\nmaterial for a lot of biosynthetic pathways including that of the\nnucleotides (ribose from the pentose-phosphate pathway). Glycolytic intermediates are also involved in the synthesis of amino\nacid, isoprenoids etc. Essentially all the carbon that cyanobacteria\ncontains comes from fixation of carbon (from CO<sub>2<\/sub>) via\nphotosynthesis.<\/li>\n<li>Cyanobacteria also store starch as an energy reserve (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23299410\" rel=\"nofollow\">Suzuki et\nal., 2013<\/a>). They also produce other polysaccharides (<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0168-6445(98)00012-6\" rel=\"nofollow\">Phillipis\nand Vincenzini, 1998<\/a>). Moreover, the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peptidoglycan\" rel=\"nofollow\">peptidoglycan<\/a> cell wall has a \"glycan\" part which is a glucose derivative (a polysaccharide).<\/li>\n<li>Moreover, cyanobacteria cannot produce ATP via the photosynthetic\nelectron transport chain in the dark and ATP in dark conditions\nis generated (though significantly less) via substrate level phosphorylation in glycolysis.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":45665,"question_id":45654,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1461785671}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45654/what-did-cyanobacteria-gain-from-photosynthesis","last_activity_date":1461785671,"creation_date":1461769057,"answer_count":2,"title":"What did cyanobacteria gain from photosynthesis?","body":"<p>As far as I understand, cyanobacteria began performing photosynthesis long before plant cells as we know them arrived on the scene. But cyanobacteria do not seem to use polysaccharides in the same way as plant cells do (building materials, for example). So what evolutionary benefit did cyanobacteria gain from photosynthesis, that could have made them continue to produce oxygen generation after generation?<\/p>\n","question_id":45654,"tags":["evolution","bacteriology","photosynthesis"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":45665,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":38,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/64c9bd2d942d3c50a87db8f8ac414aae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unr