 off-site pain actions.  In my case, it appears to be more simply the action of (for want of a better term) CrossedNerves.  As one example, there is an area of about two square inches, just right of center, on my chest which, when poked with a sharp object, will cause a stabbing  pain to appear on the back of my right shoulder just below the shoulder blade. This is repeatable and has been that way since as long as I can remember. \nGlad to see I'm not the only one with these strange biological oddities.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45526,"question_id":45502,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45502/is-it-possible-to-feel-pain-in-some-part-of-a-body-but-the-pain-feeling-is-in","last_activity_date":1461783038,"creation_date":1461363514,"answer_count":4,"title":"Is it possible to feel pain in some part of a body, but the pain \"feeling\" is introduced somewhere else?","body":"<p>Is it possible to feel pain in some part of a body, but that the cause of the pain is situated elsewhere in the body? For example, somebody feels pain in his toe, but it turns out that this pain is not signaled by nerves in his toe, but caused by a damaged nerve in the spinal cord, or somewhere in the brain.<\/p>\n","question_id":45502,"tags":["neuroscience","neurophysiology","pain","peripheral-nervous-system"],"score":13,"accepted_answer_id":45505,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1461824278,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1081,"up_vote_count":13,"last_edit_date":1461365629},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f78cdcd88b74e6ac07c168b8cefb330d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20722,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20722/city7lights","reputation":138,"display_name":"city7lights","accept_rate":62},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TSuGp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19521/jordi-zambrino","reputation"