 different question though, and most scientists would say it&#39;s too early for this yet; but this depends a lot on what specific application you&#39;re thinking of. For curing a recessive genetic disorder for example, 10% success rate might be fine. You need to be more specific I think."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KaVYs.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17527,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17527/dshulgin","reputation":144,"display_name":"dshulgin","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":45655,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461858748,"comment_id":80129,"body":"I&#39;m interesting in how we can avoid unwanted mutations that CRISPR/Cas causes."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":0,"post_id":45655,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461863849,"comment_id":80133,"body":"Well that&#39;s an entire research field ... If you&#39;re asking about the current rate of off-target effects, that can be answered (Keith Joung&#39;s paper mention by Tom is a good example). But in the study you cite, I don&#39;t see any data on off-target effects. They only looked at the CCR5 locus, and 84% of embryos that were not &quot;successful&quot; were either not edited at that locus, or contained indels (unsuccessful homology repair). So that is more about efficiency of homology repair, which is unrelated to Cas9 specificity."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=