t these problems may yet be solved. The CRISP/Cas approach to gene editing already has a lot of different variants and is under continual improvement, so there's no reason to think it won't get better. There's also no reason to think that the 16% figure there is only influenced by the use of CRISPR/Cas - it's an experiment with lots of other variables.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45656,"question_id":45655,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e8369b00e6cae124d24b2a0102bf38b1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21570,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21570/tom","reputation":26,"display_name":"Tom"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KaVYs.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17527,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17527/dshulgin","reputation":144,"display_name":"dshulgin","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":45660,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461774017,"comment_id":80047,"body":"Thanks, i will read it next day."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461773415,"creation_date":1461773415,"body":"<p>The accuracy of CRISPR to its target is not necessarily a problem at this time, because scientists have developed a more accurate version of it, CRISPR hf, which has almost no off target effects.  <a href=\"https://hms.harvard.edu/news/high-fidelity-crispr\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here's a report on a study with a very accurate version of CRISPR<\/a> <\/p>\n","answer_id":45660,"question_id":45655,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45655/crispr-cas-for-editing-the-human-genome","last_activity_date":1461773415,"creation_date":1461769269,"answer_count":2,"title":"CRISPR/Cas for editing the human genome","body":"<p>I know, that the CRISP/Cas approach for \"cutting\" the human genome is not completely suitable if we can't say not suitable at all. Because we have many repeats and this appro