at every single thing in existence evolved for a reason implies evolution is finalistic. Certain things are just not selected against, despite not giving a clear evolutionary advantage. Penicillin resistance is a good example of a trait that was positively selected, but that does not mean (as many put it) that &quot;the bacteria evolved the resistance because there were antibiotics around&quot; (finalistic view), but rather that &quot;some bacteria which happened to have the AmpR gene were more fit and expanded&quot;"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/FxxEx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13072,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13072/corvus","reputation":1501,"display_name":"Corvus"},"score":1,"post_id":7669,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1430463998,"comment_id":53865,"body":"@nico I totally agree that many traits are not adaptations. And I agree that final cause explanations are generally inappropriate forms of evolutionary explanation (though teleological language be an acceptable shorthand among researchers who are all clear on the subtleties). I think we&#39;re pretty much on the same page here."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":7669,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/FxxEx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13072,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13072/corvus","reputation":1501,"display_name":"Corvus"},"edited":false,"creation_date":145025396