://www.rsc.org/chemistryworld/Issues/2005/October/prions.asp\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.rsc.org/chemistryworld/Issues/2005/October/prions.asp<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":45641,"question_id":45629,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461754380,"creation_date":1461744653,"body":"<p>Like other forms of amyloid, aggregated prions form a beta-sheet structure, where individual beta-strands are linked together by hydrogen bonds between their extended peoptide backbones, and hydrophobic interactions between the side chains on either side of the peptide backbone.  The beta-strand at each end of the beta-sheet has unpaired hydrogen bonds and hydrophobic side chains on the exposed end, which act as a template to link with an incoming prion.  Thus an incoming prion molecule can be unfolded as it joins with the exposed beta-strand, rather like a zip, and a new exposed edge is formed, waiting for the next prion to join.<\/p>\n\n<p>This chain reaction is rather like normal crystalization, except that the process of aggregation also involves a conformational change from a folded globular molecule to an extended beta strand, which is catalyzed by the presence of existing beta-strands.  So the aggregation of prion effectively catalyzes more aggregation in a positive feedback loop: Once a seed has formed, the aggregation process will continue to unfold and recruit normal protein molecules.  Thus BSE/CJD was originally thought to be a virus as the aggregated conformation appears to be \"infectious\", passing its information about its aggregated state to a native folded prion molecule.<\/p>\n\n<p>See for example:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.bioeng.4.092801.094202\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.bioeng.4.092801.094202<\/a>\n<a href=\"http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.pathmechdis.3.121806.154326\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.pathmechdis.3.121806.154326<\/a>\n<a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v11/n3/abs/nrn2786.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v11/n3/abs/nrn2786.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Or just google \"prion aggregation mechanism review\"<\/p>\n","answer_id":45642,"question_id":45629,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461754380}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45629/how-do-prions-transmit-their-conformation-to-other-proteins","last_activity_date":1461754380,"creation_date":1461703559,"answer_count":2,"title":"How do prions transmit their conformation to other proteins?","body":"<p>I was reading about prions and many sources say something to this effect:<\/p>\n\n<p>\"Prions may propagate by transmitting their misfolded protein state: When a prion enters a healthy organism, it induces existing, properly folded proteins to convert into the misfolded prion form. In this way, the prion acts as a template to guide the misfolding of more proteins into prion form.\" (Wikipedia)<\/p>\n\n<p>How can/does a prion cause another protein to change its shape to match the prion's? <\/p>\n","question_id":45629,"tags":["proteins","pathology","protein-folding","protein-interaction","prion"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":32,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/46e198bb1856ee58a4d5defb056945d2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16594,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16594/user135172","reputation":199,"display_name":"user135172","accept_rate":80},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KaVYs.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registe