:"@user135172 just that this is not the correlation matrix. However, the concept of eigenvalues and eigenvectors is similar. Just like any linear algebra problem. If a matrix is a function applied to a vector (which may denote state of the system), then the eigenvalues somewhat denote the amplification factor of the matrix (along different directions)."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461748644,"creation_date":1461748644,"body":"<p>There is no standard notation called Q (matrix).<\/p>\n\n<p>However in this case I think the matrix that they are referring to is the state transition matrix (similar to the adjacency matrix as mentioned by Justas in the comments, but with rates instead of just the connections). Basically you have three states (lets call them <strong>A<\/strong>, <strong>B<\/strong> and <strong>C<\/strong>) and there is a rate for transition from one state to the other. You can also represent these rates in the form of transition probabilities. <\/p>\n\n<p>You just represent this as a 3×3 matrix. Put zero where there are no such transitions (for example there is no transition from <strong>A<\/strong> to <strong>A<\/strong> or <strong>A<\/strong> to <strong>C<\/strong>):<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\\begin{array}{|l|c|c|c|}\n\\hline\n &amp; A &amp; B &amp; C \\\\\\hline\nA &amp; 0 &amp; 10 &amp; 0 \\\\\\hline\nB &amp; 100 &amp; 0 &amp; 50 \\\\\\hline\nC &amp; 5 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\\\\\hline\n\\end{array}\n$$<\/p>\n\n<p>You can then calculate the eigenvalue for this matrix. How to calculate eigenvalues and what is their significance is off-topic in this site. You can easily find out how to calculate eigenvalues. Their significance is something that is not that easy to understand but you can read more about that and can perhaps ask a precise question in <a href=\"http://math.stackexchange.com/\">Mathematics Stack Exchange<\/a>. Basically, they tell you how the system proceeds in different directions (denoted by eigenvectors).<\/p>\n","answer_id":45645,"question_id":45615,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45615/a-state-model-of-sodium-channels","last_activity_date":1461748644,"creation_date":1461668180,"answer_count":1,"title":"A state model of sodium channels","body":"<p>I am studying by myself Human Physiology.\nI have encountered the following question:<\/p>\n\n<p>In the following given model of sodium channel with 3 states open closed blocked (which I assume means inactivated), the rates of going from state to stated are given in the picture below. <\/p>\n\n<p>a. Write matrix $Q$ for the system and find it's eigenvalues.\nb. What does these values represent?<\/p>\n\n<p>If anyone has an idea what is the required matrix I will be grateful.\nThanks!<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/1CNKp.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/1CNKp.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a>  <\/p>\n","question_id":45615,"tags":["physiology","homework","theoretical-biology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":38,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461746287},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0b6bb9257be3e192f7b7bdb2203c552f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23518,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23518/dr-tahir-usman","reputation":6,"display_name":"Dr. Tahir Usman"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":45637,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461741662,"comment_id":79972,"body":"I think this question is missing a few key details for it to be answerable. Do you have the NCBI IDs? A &quot;logical way&quot; will depend on protein context (membrane or globular, what is the enzymatic function, etc). Would the super-kingdoms be enough resolution?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/45195875d9ed18788474bdae5d9d67b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3827,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3827/skymningen","reputation":1558,"display_name":"skymningen"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461746940,"creation_date":1461746940,"body":"<p>This is basically metagenomics.\nCongratulations, you already did the most time consuming step. \nThere are several ways to go from there, but I will talk about the one I know best.\nThere is the metagenomic analysis tool <a href=\"http://ab.inf.uni-tuebingen.de/data/software/megan6/download/welcome.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">MEGAN<\/a>. It can read your Blast Output, if it is in the correct format (normal XML or tabular) and will automatically do what you want. \nFor a start, just use the default values, for more help you an then go to the <a href=\"http://megan.informatik.uni-tuebingen.de\" rel=\"nofollow\">Community Website<\/a> of MEGAN for help.<\/p>\n\n<p>Analysing your data may take a little, depending on how many contigs you have. But if you were able to blast them in reasonable time it should be no problem. As I said, you are through the most time consuming step already.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45644,"question_id":45637,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45637/taxonomic-clasification-of-blast-output","last_activity_date":1461746940,"creation_date":1461740397,"answer_count":1,"title":"Taxonomic clasification of BLAST output","body":"<p>I am working with Next Generation Sequencing. I BLASTed the bovine de novo assembled contigs to the NCBI nucleotide database. I got a matching with a lot of species i.e. different kind of bacteria, viruses and mammals. I want them to group in a logical way i.e. all the bacteria in one group (bacteria group) similarly viruses and mammals. This is hard to arrange manually, can anybody help how I can arrange my vast number of species into some logical grouping. Thanking in anticipation.<\/p>\n","question_id":45637,"tags":["bioinformatics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":24,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1461745698},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":2,"post_id":45589,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461609509,"comment_id":79868,"body":"Because breaking H2O into H2 and O2 is an endothermic reaction: that is, it takes energy to break the bonds.  Food has molecules that can be broken down, or combined with other molecules such as oxygen, in exothermic (that is, energy producing) reactions."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"score":1,"post_id":45601,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461783377,"comment_id":80061,"body":"Oh, that&#39;s really clear! So to attempt to parrot it back to you: animals that eat food are turning high-energy bonds into low-energy bonds, and using the energy that results. The low-energy bonds that get created in this process are in things like water and CO2, which get turned into high-energy bonds again by plants (they get the extra energy from sunlight)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"score":1,"post_id":45601,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461783380,"comment_id":80062,"body":"So if something is &quot;food&quot; to an animal, it&#39;s probably because it has a lot of high-energy bonds."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"score":0,"post_id":45601,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461793317,"comment_id":80066,"body":"Yes, that pretty much sums it up.  Ultimately, food stores energy in high energy bonds, and we extract the energy by breaking them and replacing them with low energy bonds in CO2 and water.  In fact most organic compounds contain high energy bonds, which is why they burn in air to give out energy (the heat and light of a flame), although we haven&#39;t evolved the enzymes to use them all as food."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"score":0,"post_id":45601,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461810256,"comment_id":80076,"body":"So we&#39;re talking about bonds that have a lot of potential energy. Are these always bonds that are easy to break, or do the two categories just have some overlap but are unrelated?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"score":0,"post_id":45601,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461826177,"comment_id":80083,"body":"The energy of a bond and whether it is easy to break are not directly linked as it depends on the energy of the transition state, but generally the more energy stored in the bond, the easier it is to break and the less energy required to break it via the transition state.  However most enzymes work by reducing the energy of the transition state so that bonds break and form more easily, and thus they speed up the reaction."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"score":0,"post_id":45601,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8c8eafb6f5b02a0e67f2a6186d761bfb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23481/eli-rose","reputation":109,"display_name":"Eli Rose"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461827543,"comment_id":80086,"body":"PS. A good example to illustrate this, is that gasoline does not spontaneosly combust in air, you need an initial spark to pass through the transition state, then the energy released allows the rest of the reaction to proceed via the transition state.  Similarly, glucose does not spontaneously combust in air and you need enzymes to reduce the energy of the transition state so that the reaction goes at body temperature."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1461625571,"creation_date":1461620429,"body":"<p>You don't get energy from breaking chemical bonds, you only get energy from making chemical bonds, while breaking chemical bonds requires the input of energy.  However, in practice chemical bonds are always broken as others are formed, and the net number of bonds is generally constant.  Otherwise you would end up with free radicals, which are highly reactive and looking to form a chemical bond with the next thing it touches.<\/p>\n\n<p>For example, the burning of glucose in respiration involves the breaking of C-C, C-H, C-O and O-H bonds in glucose and O=O bonds in oxygen, with the simultaneous formation of C=O bonds in CO2 and O-H bonds in water.  But the C=O bonds in CO2 and O-H bonds in water contain much less energy than the bonds we break within in glucose.  So the key is that the bonds formed contain less energy than the bonds broken, and energy is released overall.<\/p>\n\n<p>And actually it's a bit more complicated than that, because you also have to consider entropy, which is how disordered the system is.  Generally the more molecules in a system, the more entropy, so breaking a few big molecules down into lots of small molecules tends to release energy by increasing entropy.<\/p>\n\n<p>So to answer your question, \"food\" is what we can draw useful energy from in the process of turning it into something else as we make and break chemical bonds.  We can't do this with water, or indeed with rocks, because their chemical bonds would require more energy to break than the energy we'd get back out by forming alternative bonds with anything else.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45601,"question_id":45589,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1461625571},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/LBnjL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22415,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22415/graham-chiu","reputation":254,"display_name":"Graham Chiu"},"score":-2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"score":0,"post_id":45638,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461746430,"comment_id":79988,"body":"&quot;Plants use both water and air as food using photosynthesis ... to make glucose.&quot; - No, glucose itself is the &quot;food&quot; that is burned with oxygen in respiration, while CO2 and water are used by plants to make the glucose food by photosynthesis with the sun&#39;s energy.  Water and air could never be described as &quot;food&quot;.  Food is what you get energy <i>from<\/i> by oxidation (burning it with oxygen)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/LBnjL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22415,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22415/graham-chiu","reputation":254,"display_name":"Graham Chiu"},"score":0,"post_id":45638,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23467/kelvin","reputation":148,"display_name":"Kelvin"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461750709,"comment_id":79999,"body":"The Cambridge dictionary disagrees with you."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7ced00ee0d98a2971462c140084e4b5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23467,"li