ast_activity_date":1461740757,"creation_date":1461598316,"answer_count":2,"title":"What makes something food?","body":"<p>From my (limited) understanding, animals get energy from food by breaking chemical bonds between molecules.<\/p>\n\n<p>There's a lot of water here <sup>[<em>citation needed<\/em>]<\/sup>, so it seems like natural selection would favor any organism that could live off it. Why, in the history of life on earth, hasn't an organism appeared that eats water?<\/p>\n\n<p>Same applies to dirt, rocks -- (although maybe lichen eat rocks? I'm fuzzy on lichen.)<\/p>\n\n<p>Or air?<\/p>\n\n<p>Why are humans and other animals like us only equipped to eat certain types of molecules, when others are so much more plentiful?<\/p>\n","question_id":45589,"tags":["human-biology","biochemistry","food"],"score":-1,"accepted_answer_id":45601,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_count":86,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1461608296},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/54a82fba3ce9f146c47e561b973f6adf?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5851,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5851/caters","reputation":341,"display_name":"Caters","accept_rate":36},"closed_date":1461725898,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/54a82fba3ce9f146c47e561b973f6adf?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5851,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5851/caters","reputation":341,"display_name":"Caters","accept_rate":36},"score":0,"post_id":45609,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461742019,"comment_id":79976,"body":"There must be an explanation for this. I can&#39;t find it online(already researched &quot;wasps a few days after bees&quot;).  So why was this put on hold as opinion based? Was it because of me referring to multiple types of wasps(hornets and yellow jackets)? Was it because of my multiple ideas about why I see wasps after I see bees?"}],"link":"http://biolo