"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":45492,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461561230,"comment_id":79836,"body":"From you definition, a &quot;holey&quot; is just an adjective to describe the general shape of a landscape. Note that you don&#39;t define &quot;rugged&quot; landscape. It is unclear to me why GAMs would not do it."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45492/is-there-a-package-or-a-software-to-calculate-an-holey-fitness-landscape","last_activity_date":1461725886,"creation_date":1461339165,"answer_count":0,"title":"Is there a package or a software to calculate an holey fitness landscape?","body":"<p>The holey landscape is interesting to enable the population to move from an adaptive peak to another <a href=\"http://www.paperin.org/research/hfl\" rel=\"nofollow\">without crossing a valley of low fitness<\/a>. A fitness landscape is computable in R with a <a href=\"https://www.zoology.ubc.ca/~schluter/R/fit-model/\" rel=\"nofollow\">GAM model and plotting<\/a> phenotypic information and fitness. But I haven\u2019t found a package or software to calculate a holey landscape. <code>Gavrilets, S. 2003. Models of speciation: what have we learned in 40 years? Evolution 57:2197\u20132215.<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Definition of holey adaptive landscape:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>A holey adaptive landscape is defined as an adaptive landscape where\n  relatively infrequent high-fitness genotypes form a contigu- ous set\n  that expands throughout the genotype space<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>From <code>Gavrilets, S. 2003. Models of speciation: what have we learned in 40 years? Evolution 57:2197\u20132215.<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Definition of fitness landscape: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In evolutionary biology, fitness landscapes or adaptive landscapes\n  (types of Evolutionary landscapes) are used to visualize the\n  relationship between genotypes and reproductive success. It is assumed\n  that every genotype has a well-defined replication rate (often\n  referred to as fitness). This fitness is the \"height\" of the\n  landscape. Genotypes which are very similar are said to be \"close\" to\n  each other, while those that are very different are \"far\" from each\n  other. The set of all possible genotypes, their degree of similarity,\n  and their related fitness values is then called a fitness landscape.\n  The idea of a fitness landscape is a metaphor to help explain flawed\n  forms in evolution, including exploits and glitches in animals like\n  their reactions to supernormal stimuli.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>From <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fitness_landscape#cite_note-Wright-1\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Do you know if there is a way to do this with a package or software?<\/p>\n","question_id":45492,"tags":["evolution","bioinformatics","ecology","fitness"],"score":-1,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":false,"view_count":41,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461725886},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8bbc94977312d285045b2412257b6cb8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1195,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1195/kenorb","reputation":285,"display_name":"kenorb","accept_rate":67},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":5,"post_id":45626,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461697806,"comment_id":79951,"body":"Nope, it does not. Alcohol is resorbed by the body and metablized. Additionally, to kill bacteria, you need 70% alcohol - which is a very bad idea to have this concentration in your body."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7258cbf9bfcfd112bb90d1e55f8dd1a7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19468,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19468/rha","reputation":316,"display_name":"RHA"},"score":0,"post_id":45626,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461698613,"comment_id":79952,"body":"@Chris That looks like an answer disguised as a comment..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":45626,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7258cbf9bfcfd112bb90d1e55f8dd1a7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19468,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19468/rha","reputation":316,"display_name":"RHA"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461698740,"comment_id":79953,"body":"@RHA At the moment it&#39;s a comment. It doesn&#39;t have any references or whatever, maybe I find some time later to write a real answer. In this  case I will delete my comment."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/09e1698b400a42719f9fa23e35aa3fa6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23206,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23206/m-carter","reputation":93,"display_name":"M. Carter"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stacke