do not have to be straight lines, see the neuraxis:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/DKN92.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/DKN92.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":45584,"question_id":45568,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461597716,"creation_date":1461597716,"body":"<p>The so called horizontal axis (rosto-caudal) is parallel to the body of the rat.  Vertical is just vertical when the rat is in its normal standing position and medio-lateral is horizonral and perpendicular to the rat's body. The head is the origin.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45588,"question_id":45568,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45568/spatial-dimensions-for-an-animal","last_activity_date":1461597716,"creation_date":1461543136,"answer_count":2,"title":"Spatial dimensions for an animal","body":"<p>I'm reading a review paper. They say:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The position of an object in head-centered coordinates (that is, relative to an animal's head) can be defined along three axes: the medio-lateral (radial) axis, the rostro-caudal (horizontal) axis and the dorso-central (vertical) axis.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I'm having a little bit of difficulty understanding this coordinate system as the paper doesn't provide a picture. Usually I would think of the three axis as an x-y-z coordinate system where the rat's head is the \"origin\" (from a mathematical standpoint), but the terminology here seems to be a bit different, so I'd like to understand from a biologist's point-of-view how these three axes are drawn relative from a rat's head.<\/p>\n\n<p>Paper can be found here: <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/